<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF95FFFFFE80B94EFCA3A6D2" blockId="11.[282,1783,1640,2646]" pageId="11" pageNumber="348">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF95FFFFFE80B94EFE5EA8CE" box="[368,460,1912,1948]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="348">Male</emphasis>
(ad.). — Labium bluish- or yellowish-white. Labrum, mandible-bases, anteclypeus and genae pale greenish- or bluish-white, this colour narrowly continued upwards against the margin of compound eyes; labrum shining, finely bordered with brown anteriorly. Postclypeus and frons dark bronzy-brown, lustreless; vertex and epicranium dull metallic-green. Torulus of antennae blackish-brown surrounded by a paler area which extends rearwards and a little inwards as an indistinct, slightly curved, rusty-brown stripe, ceasing on the outer side of each lateral ocellus. Antennae dark brown, pedicel pale brown, darkened apically. Occipital plate with two small pits, one on each side. Rear of the head black, pruinose.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3076562FF95FFF9FE83B7A6FA30A6B7" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="350" pageId="11" pageNumber="348" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF95FFFFFE83B7A6FB40A6B8" blockId="11.[282,1783,1640,2646]" pageId="11" pageNumber="348">Prothorax clear blue, anterior and posterior lobes dark brown, propleurae pale vinaceous-fawn (Ridgway), slightly pruinose.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF95FFF8FE81B7CDF9E6AEA5" blockId="11.[282,1783,1640,2646]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="349" pageId="11" pageNumber="348">
Synthorax dull bronzy-black with slight greenish reflections above. Dorsal pale markings sharply defined, and of a delicate calamine-blue. Ante-alar triangles filled in with blue. The sides, beyond the humeral suture, are less vividly coloured, usually burn blue or light glaucous blue with two parallel, oblique, tawny bands which at times are very indistinct (
<figureCitation id="13262A6CFF92FFF8FAE3BFABFA0BAE93" box="[1299,1433,413,449]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">fig. 4 c</figureCitation>
). Metepimeron and under surfaces pale glaucous blue, thinly pruinose in aged individuals.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF92FFF8FEA6BEFEF920AFB9" box="[342,1714,200,236]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
M. A. Lieftinck: 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FD54BEFEF9AEAFBE" box="[676,1596,200,236]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
Descriptions and records of S.E. Asiatic 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8FA6ABEFEF9A5AFBE" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1793" box="[1434,1591,200,236]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Odonata</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
<pageNumber id="BBB63D3FFF92FFF8F987BEFDF920AFB9" ambiguity="2" box="[1655,1714,203,235]" fuzzyness="0" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" score="254.0" value="349">349</pageNumber>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF92FFF8FEC3BC3FFC56AD32" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">Legs vinaceous-buff, the tibiae usually rather more pale olive-buff; spines, and apices of all femora, dark brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF92FFF8FEC2BC42FE2FAB3C" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
Wings very different in shape from those of 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FB90BC42FA47ADCA" box="[1120,1493,628,664]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8FB90BC42FA99ADCA" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[1120,1291,628,664]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">orientalis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8FAD2BC42FA47ADCA" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1889" box="[1314,1493,628,664]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysopus">chrysopus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8F9C8BC42FEB3AD9F" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8F9C8BC42FE88AD9F" authorityName="M.A. Lieftinck" authorityYear="1940" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buwaldai" status="sp. n.">buwaldai</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
more abruptly expanded beyond the petiole, decidedly broader and with the apices broadly and rather abruptly rounded 1). Distance between base of wing and Ax1 only little longer than the space between 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FB87BD21FB2BAC69" box="[1143,1209,791,827]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">Axl</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FAE9BD21FAF3AC69" box="[1305,1377,791,827]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">Ax2</emphasis>
(about 1 1/3 in fore wing, less than 11/2 in hinder wing). Quadrilateral much longer than in 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8F9BABD78FEA9ACF8" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8F9BABD78FEBDACF8" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">orientalis</taxonomicName>
;
</emphasis>
costal side in fore wing twice as long, and in hind wing almost three times as long as distal side. Two postquadrangular antenodal cells in all wings. Pterostigma light to dark brown, distinctly shorter than in 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FA88BDC3F9BBAB4B" box="[1400,1577,1013,1049]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8FA88BDC3F9B6AB4B" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[1400,1572,1013,1049]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">orientalis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Nodal index15-18/14-18.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF92FFF8FEC1BAB6F99AAAEB" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
Abdomen short, shaped and coloured much as in 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FB00BAB6FA32ABF6" box="[1264,1440,1152,1188]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8FB00BAB6FA0EABF6" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[1264,1436,1152,1188]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">orientalis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Segm. 1 pale brown, sides bluish-white; 2 with the dorso-basal calamine-blue mark slightly less deeply indented posteriorly, sides pale blue. Remaining segments similar to 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FEE9BB11FE5BAA19" box="[281,457,1319,1355]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8FEE9BB11FE56AA19" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[281,452,1319,1355]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">orientalis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Segm. 7 - 1 0 less obscured than in that species and with traces of blue mid-dorsal spots at extreme base only. Tenth segment roof-shaped, dark brown above; sides of 9 and 10 indistinctly marked with pale blue.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF92FFF8FEC2BBFAFC8DA8B6" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
Sup. anal apps. dark reddish brown, apical third black. Basal third of inferior pair yellow, the remainder shining black. Superior pair shorter than the inferiors, of simple structure; apices truncated. Inferior pair broad and contiguous basally, thence narrowed and somewhat outbent on middle, finally again widened and provided interiorly with a stout tooth-like projection that meets its fellow of the opposite side so as to embrace an oval notch; apices strongly divergent, bluntly pointed; seen from the side the appendage thickens to a knob whose upper surface is hollowed out in part and bears a small corrugated area, which, in aged individuals, is densely covered with a whitish, granular, pruinescence (
<figureCitation id="13262A6CFF92FFF8FD6DB9F6FC9AA8B6" box="[669,776,1984,2020]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[370,432,1622,1654]" captionTargetBox="[366,1652,766,1608]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig. 5. Podolestes coomansi, sp. n. ♂. Anal appendages, dorsal view and right side." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3571128" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3571128/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF92FFF8FEC0B9C3FC86A703" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FEC0B9C3FE21A74B" box="[304,435,2037,2073]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">Female</emphasis>
(ad.). — Closely similar to the male in colour and markings, but abdomen more robustly built.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF92FFF9FEC0B657FCA4AED1" lastBlockId="13.[263,1759,294,736]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="350" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">The dorsum of the synthorax is raw umber instead of bronzy-black, a narrow stripe over the median carina being Sanford’s brown in colour. Mesepimeral blue patches (antehumeral spots), very slightly larger than in the male, only little longer than broad.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF92FFF8FED7B6D9FD39A519" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
1) Neither Munz’s nor Ris’s figures of the wings of the suposed ♂ and ♀ of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8F92BB6D9FEE9A661" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">
P 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FF2EB725FEE9A661" bold="true" box="[222,379,2323,2355]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">orientalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
agree exactly with those o f true examples of this species from Borneo, Billiton and South Sumatra, described by me in a previous paper (
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FA9EB700F9EEA604" bold="true" box="[1390,1660,2358,2390]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">loc. cit., antea).</emphasis>
In our series both pairs o f wings are narrower and decidedly more pointed apically than it would appear from these illustrations. On the other hand, the apices o f the wings of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8FEE5B796FE74A692" authorityName="M.A. Lieftinck" authorityYear="1940" box="[277,486,2464,2496]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coomansi">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FEE5B796FE74A692" bold="true" box="[277,486,2464,2496]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">P. coomansi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are still more rounded off than in the two specimens o f 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8F9E6B796F921A692" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[1558,1715,2464,2496]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8F9E6B796F921A692" bold="true" box="[1558,1715,2464,2496]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">orientalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
examined by Munz and Ris, so that there may exist yet another Malaysian species of 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FF2DB7D1FE00A555" bold="true" box="[221,402,2535,2567]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8FF2DB7D1FE18A555" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[221,394,2535,2567]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Podolestes</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
intermediate in this respect between 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8FBC9B7D1FB45A555" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[1081,1239,2535,2567]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FBC9B7D1FB45A555" bold="true" box="[1081,1239,2535,2567]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">orientalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FACDB7D1FA4FA555" bold="true" box="[1341,1501,2535,2567]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF92FFF8FACDB7D1FA4AA555" authorityName="M.A. Lieftinck" authorityYear="1940" box="[1341,1496,2535,2567]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coomansi">coomansi</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
(See 
<author id="53A0DE0CFF92FFF8F9BEB7DCF93EA554" box="[1614,1708,2538,2566]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">Munz</author>
, 
<journalOrPublisher id="51DC3C25FF92FFF8FF2FB43DFDF6A579" box="[223,612,2571,2603]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">Mem. Amer. Ent. Soc.</journalOrPublisher>
<part id="FFB99C74FF92FFF8FD87B43DFD19A579" box="[631,651,2571,2603]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">3</part>
, Philad. 
<year id="FFB577BAFF92FFF8FCC2B43DFCECA579" box="[818,894,2571,2603]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">1919</year>
, 
<pagination id="B2D4C81DFF92FFF8FC69B43DFC6BA579" box="[921,1017,2571,2603]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">pl. 10</pagination>
<bookContentInfo id="BCE62599FF92FFF8FBFFB43DFB1AA579" box="[1039,1160,2571,2603]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">fig. 60</bookContentInfo>
; and 
<author id="53A0DE0CFF92FFF8FB07B43DFAA2A579" box="[1271,1328,2571,2603]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">Ris</author>
, 
<journalOrPublisher id="51DC3C25FF92FFF8FABDB43DF93FA579" box="[1357,1709,2571,2603]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">Zool. Meded. Leiden</journalOrPublisher>
, 
<part id="FFB99C74FF92FFF8FF2EB41DFE97A519" box="[222,261,2603,2635]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349" type="volume">10</part>
, 
<year id="FFB577BAFF92FFF8FED0B41DFEF8A519" box="[288,362,2603,2635]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">1927</year>
, 
<pagination id="B2D4C81DFF92FFF8FE74B406FD9CA519" box="[388,526,2603,2635]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF92FFF8FE74B406FE0DA518" bold="true" box="[388,415,2608,2634]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">p.</emphasis>
15- 16
</pagination>
, 
<figureCitation id="13262A6CFF92FFF8FDDDB41DFD0AA519" box="[557,664,2603,2635]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="17.[225,275,1195,1223]" captionTargetBox="[228,1073,591,1173]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Fig. 7. Coeliccia arcuata, sp. n. ♂. Anal ap ­ pendages, dorsal view and right side ." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3571133" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3571133/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">
<bookContentInfo id="BCE62599FF92FFF8FDDDB41DFD0AA519" box="[557,664,2603,2635]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">fig. 7</bookContentInfo>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF92FFF8F905B6D9F969A65D" box="[1781,1787,2287,2319]" pageId="12" pageNumber="349">.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF93FFF9FEF7BEF6FA8CAFB3" blockId="13.[263,1758,188,239]" box="[263,1310,192,225]" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">
<pageNumber id="BBB63D3FFF93FFF9FEF7BEF6FED0AFB2" ambiguity="4" box="[263,322,192,224]" fuzzyness="0" pageId="13" pageNumber="350" score="252.0" value="350">350</pageNumber>
Treubia Deel 17, 1940, Afl. 4.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF93FFF9FEACBFA3FC26AD67" blockId="13.[263,1759,294,736]" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">
Wings hyaline or slightly enfumed with obscured border beyond 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF93FFF9F9C7BFA3F9C9AEEB" box="[1591,1627,405,441]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">pt</emphasis>
in old specimens; similar in shape to the male or even a little broader. Neuration as in the opposite sex. Nodal index13-16/14-16.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF93FFF9FEABBC66FE4BA8E6" blockId="13.[263,1759,294,736]" lastBlockId="13.[261,1758,766,2133]" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">Abdomen coloured similarly to the male. Apical segments dark brown, almost black in old specimens, with bronzy-green or -blue reflections. Blue basal spot of segm. 2 only shallowly indented posteriorly, those on 3 - 7 slightly enlarged and all blue mid-dorsally. Segm. 8 with narrow, complete, blue basal annule, the blue colour extending finely along the mid-dorsal carina as far as the middle of the segment; 9 with the blue basal annule still narrower, incomplete laterally, but with the median off-shoot stouter, extending almost to end of segment.</paragraph>
<caption id="DF626661FF93FFF9FE82B860FBD4A9C8" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3571128" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3571128" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3571128/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="350" startId="13.[370,432,1622,1654]" targetBox="[366,1652,766,1608]" targetPageId="13">
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF93FFF9FE82B860FBD4A9C8" blockId="13.[261,1758,766,2133]" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">
Fig. 5. 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF93FFF9FDF8B860FCF4A924" bold="true" box="[520,870,1622,1654]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF93FFF9FDF8B860FCCCA924" authorityName="M.A. Lieftinck" authorityYear="1940" box="[520,862,1622,1654]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="13" pageNumber="350" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coomansi" status="sp. n.">Podolestes coomansi</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A25A5780FF93FFF9FC8AB860FC4AA924" box="[890,984,1622,1654]" pageId="13" pageNumber="350" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
♂. Anal appendages, dorsal view and right side.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF93FFF9FEA9B9F0F926A707" blockId="13.[261,1758,766,2133]" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">Anal appendages almost as long as segm. 10, rather swollen, but tips acutely pointed. Valves brown, of simple structure, not surpassing end of segm. 10. Length: ♂ abd. + app. 29-31.5, hw. 22 -24; ♀ 27.5-29; 23.8-25 mm.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF93FFF9FEA9B6B6FA30A6B7" blockId="13.[260,1758,2173,2641]" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">
This fine new species is chiefly remarkable for its colouring and for the peculiar, broadly rounded wings. The ♂ is easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF93FFF9FA0FB680F94CA788" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[1535,1758,2230,2266]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="13" pageNumber="350" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF93FFF9FA0FB680F94CA788" box="[1535,1758,2230,2266]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">P. orientalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Selys, by the different shape of its anal appendages, whilst the 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF93FFF9F9F6B6DAF989A642" box="[1542,1563,2284,2320]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">9</emphasis>
resembles the ♂ in that the antehumeral blue bands on the dorsum of the mesothorax are in the form of isolated, oval (or wedge-shaped) patches, whereas in the ♀ of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF93FFF9FEF5B7BAFE3FA6E2" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[261,429,2444,2480]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Podolestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="13" pageNumber="350" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF93FFF9FEF5B7BAFE3FA6E2" box="[261,429,2444,2480]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">orientalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are band-like, widest ventrally and bluntly pointed above, occupying the lower two-thirds of the mesepisternite (
<figureCitation id="13262A6CFF93FFF9FAF6B7F7FA11A6B7" box="[1286,1411,2497,2533]" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">fig. 4d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3076562FF93FFF9FEA9B7C1FB04A503" pageId="13" pageNumber="350" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF93FFF9FEA9B7C1FB04A503" blockId="13.[260,1758,2173,2641]" pageId="13" pageNumber="350">Named in honour of Mr. L. Coomans de Ruiter, of Manado (Celebes), in recognition of his continuous help and activity.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
